"  Aren't __all__ scenes supposed to advance plot?
"  Not necessarily. The Kress Swimming Pool Theory of Fiction comes into play here. This theory says that scene order is like kicking off from the side of a swimming pool. The harder the initial kick, the longer and further you can glide. A first scene with conflict and action and rapid introduction of new information earns you the right to a slower following scene that adds backfill and focuses on comparative subtleties of tone, character, setting, or motif. Scene two of "Oranges" is all exposition."
*  One Damn Thing After Another
@  Nancy Kress

