-  "Or the story would be over"
"  "Character is plot," said Henry James, who did pretty well with both. My translation of this is "Why are these people doing what they're doing?" Understanding the motivations of all your major characters, not just the protagonist, can suggest plot developments. Plot and character--the double helix of fiction. So, I asked myself, the man that Harry snares and forcibly brings back to 1989--what does __that__ character want?
"  Not Jackie. Or the story would be over.
"  Okay, start here. He doesn't want Jackie. Why not? Because their personalities clash. Because the man has a life in his own time. Because he's married. Yes--that would fit with poor Harry's attempts: well-meaning but inept. After all, if Harry were good at time travel, he'd bring back not oranges but stock certificates, and end up rich. Harry, however, is not that sort of man ("Plot is character"). Harry, even when ating out of love, screws up ("Plot is one damned thing after another").
