-  Types of tempo
"  _Normal tempo_ is the conventional balance between the realistic slowness of most human happenings and the need to compress these happenings to fit the limitations of the reader's patience. _Retarded tempo_ expands time, often to a pace far slower than real time, to allow the writer to examine events in great details.
"  [...]
"  _Accelerated tempo_ is the pace of the action-adventure tale or the documentary history, the furious rush of events the leaves the hero (and the reader) breathless. Tempo is not necessarily uniform throughout the story; its variation in conformity with the author's intentions is part of his craft, something he achieves as much through stylistics devices as through his selection and arrangement of events in the plot.
*  Paragons
@  Robin Wilson

